<subSubSection lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1895,2031]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1895,1922]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Arista with 1 or 2 ventral branches (ch.6-1); posterior postgonite present only on right side of aedeagal sheath, short, apically blunt, and left lateral lobe long, broad, somewhat sinuated, apically with very large, trifurcated, anterior postgonite (“Figs 17, 18” in 
<bibRefCitation author="Chen" box="[637,841,1967,1995]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Chen" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="419 - 429" refId="ref34109" refString="Chen, H. W., Toda, M. J. &amp; Gao, J. J. (2005 b) The Phortica (s. str.) foliiseta species-complex (Diptera, Drosophilidae) from China and its adjacent countries. Acta Zootaxonomica Sinica, 30, 419 - 429." type="journal article" year="2005" yearSuffix="b">
Chen 
<emphasis box="[703,752,1968,1994]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">et al</emphasis>
. 2005b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,1895,2031]" lastBlockId="32.[151,1437,153,324]" lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,522,2003,2030]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Supplementary description</emphasis>
(not repeating characters common to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gong, Zhu &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2018" box="[939,1116,2004,2031]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zhangyuanae">
<emphasis box="[939,956,2005,2030]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[968,1116,2004,2030]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">zhangyuanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Supracervical setae 20–22. Apical, leaf-like expansion of arista apically pointed or with minute, awn-like projection. Cibarial, medial sensilla 7–8 per side. All tarsi with gray tarsomeres IV and V.
</paragraph>
